Article_title: Species delimitation in Amblyosyllis (Annelida, Syllidae)
GeneticMarker: mtDNA, other nuclear, the nuclear is 28S (D1)
Comments: 2 species have a wide geographic distribution.
Larva: Brooding, Not sure - need to look up elsewhere, For A. speciosa, dioecious and epigamous (reproductive individuals with posterior segments full of gametes and enlarged eyes), the fertilization is external, females brood egg masses (during at least five consecutive reproductive processes), and the juveniles develop without free-living larval previous stages. A. anae also lacks larval stage. Probably all of them.
Habitat: Amblyosyllis species have been found in the intertidal and subtidal zones (0–200 m), on a large variety of substrates and in association with different organisms (rocky shores, coarse sand, algae, ascidians, bryozoans, sponges, mollusks, etc.). Very little is known about the diet of most syllids, but some members of Amblyosyllis have been observed feeding on sponges.

need to check for larvae (probably broodigng) 
Asellota are easily overlooked during sampling as most species are less than 10 mm long. They represent one of the most numerous and important elements of the benthos in all oceans, especially in the deep. 
one of the most widespread acanthaspidiid isopods on the Antarctic shelf, possibly with a circum-Antarctic distribution (Brandt 1991a). However, several spécimens assigned to the same species were also found on the Australian shelf
All have no eyes, and most of them are typically found in depths below
1000 m
animals were caught using an epibenthic sledge or an Agassiz trawl

predominantly coastal marine fishes that reproduce in  estuaries, bays or open sea, where eggs are dispersed by currents

The king weakfish, Macrodon ancylodon ...  abundance and its wide consumer acceptance (Cervigón 1993; Haimovici et al. 1996; Isaac & Braga 1999).The bottom-feeding  M. ancylodon  is distributed in a wide
geographical area along the Atlantic coast of South America. It is found from the Gulf of Paria in Venezuela to Bahia Blanca in Argentina. The distribution ranges from 10 N to 40 °, and approximately 10 000 km of coastline (Fig. 1). 
This species has restricted migratory habit and inhabits coastal and estuarine areas (Yamaguti 1979). It spawns near river deltas since estuary areas are used as nursery grounds and areas where juveniles remain until the beginning of sexual maturity (Yamaguti 1979; Camargo-Zorro 1999)

Article_title: Sympatric size variants of the microcopepod Oncaea venusta exhibit distinct lineages in DNA sequences
relativeDistribution: Sympatric, he analyses focused on sympatric specicmens but probably exist also in allopatry (some localities do not have all clades, but samples sizes small o establish)
Comments:
Microcopepods. 
intro: differences in spatio-teporal distributions of morphotypes (i.e. CS, as shown in paper) indicate diff environments :In the Red Sea, the small morph is distributed in the entire basin, whereas the large morph is restricted to the southernmost Red Sea during most seasons, reaching the central area only during winter as an allochthonous species from the south (Bo¨ ttger-Schnack 1995). Also, there is a tendency for vertical separation: the small morph is distributed deeper in the water column than the large morph, which is confined mainly to the upper epipelagic zone (Bo¨ ttger-Schnack 2001).).
The high levels of sequence divergence under sympatric conditions indicated that at least the two main groups, the large and the small one, may be assigned to different species . For the medium-size group
additional morphological studies and more sensitive nuclear markers are required to clarify their taxonomic status. large specimens are identical with O. venusta forma typica (sensu Farran 1929), but small ones do not correspond to Farran’s definition of forma venella (see Bo¨ ttger-Schnack and Huys 2004).
Divergence estimated 17000 years ago (caution required).
size différences are diagnostic for the two clades small and large (not for intermediate sizes).

Article_authors: Casu, M; Curini-Galletti, M
Article_title: Genetic evidence for the existence of cryptic species in the mesopsammic flatworm Pseudomonocelis ophiocephala (Rhabditophora : Proseriata)
Article_journal: BIOLOGICAL JOURNAL OF THE LINNEAN SOCIETY
Comments:
meiofauna
The siblings of the P. ophiocephala species complex are characterized by different geographical range and/ or habitat. Sibling A occurs in moderately exposed sédiments with coarse to medium granulometry across the whole Mediterranean. Sibling B is found exclusively in the presence of the ‘banquette’ of the seagrass Posidonia oceanica in the Corsican–Sardinian region and Elba Island (western Mediterranean). Siblings C and D occur in low-energy, silty sediments on the west and east coast of Greece (eastern Mediterranean), respectively.

- an abundant Mediterranean shallow water species (Murina, 1981), is among the Monocelidinae with wide distribution and plastic ecology.

Comments: Hornell (1916) described five pseudo-species or varieties under Turbinella pyrum viz. including the Linnaeus type: var. obtusa, var. acuta, var. fusus, var. globosa and var. comorinensis. All of these five forms have their own particular geographic distribution and physical and biologic environmental characteristics (Hornell 1915). Later, Winckworth (1939) classified these varieties based on their anatomy and described var. obtusa in the synonymy of T. pyrum (Linnaeus, 1767) and var. acuta and var. globosa in the synonymy of Turbinella rapa (Lamarck, 1816).
